WHAT'S CHANGEDWaypoint REIT Ltd (WPR.AX)FromToPrice TargetA$2.50A$2.65Bull CaseA$3.76A$3.87Base CaseA$2.79A$2.87Bear CaseA$1.86A$2.05Updated ComponentsEPS and FFOBull Base Bear Scenarios
Risk Reward for Waypoint REIT Ltd (WPR.AX) has been updated

We have updated our WPR forecasts for the 1H25 result. In particular, we have (i) adjusted our share count to factor in WPR's buyback to date, and assumed that the remainder of the \(\mathsf{A}\$ 50m\) program is executed in 2H25, (ii) assumed \(\mathsf{A}\$ 35m\) of asset sales in 2H, with no further sales factored in, and (iii) updated our interest expense profile for WPR's current hedging.
Our FY25 EPS is now 16.67c (was 16.48c), slightly ahead of 16.64c guidance, and our FY26 EPS is up \(+0.8\%\) driven by lower share count.

From here, the focus for WPR will be around re- leasing upcoming expiries, with the IPO portfolio having first maturities in Aug '26. Mgmt have stated that most of the more challenged sites have already been sold and that neutral spreads are not out of the question on the FY26 basket of expiries; our forecasts assume a conservative - 5% spread.
We lift our PT to \(\mathsf{A}\$ 2.65\) (was \(\mathsf{A}\$ 2.50\) ) driven by (i) higher free cash forecasts in our DCF, and (ii) factoring in buyback to our bull/base/bear valuations.

Despite WPR's long WALE nature, we hold a cautious view on the stock for three reasons: (i) limited capital deployment opportunities - with capex programs somewhat controlled by tenants; (ii) expiry uncertainties - with Viva leases starting to mature from 2026 with leasing spreads since IPO averaging - 4.4%; and (iii) uncertainty over the longer- term relevance of the sites as electric vehicles will gain greater market share. Its WALE has also progressively declined since establishment, now at around 7 years vs. 15 years at IPO.
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research
Disruption: Negative Electric Vehicles: Negative View descriptions of Risk Rewards Themes here

In this scenario, we assume flat rental reversion upon renewals (2026+). This implies a good 4%/year CAGR at retail sales, and also flat fuel profits (relative to 2016) - this is a bullish view given volumes have dropped 20- 30% since the portfolio was first established in 2016.
We assume only 10% of sites will have no value due to technology in the longer term.
InguNAV, we apply 100bps of cap rate compression.
We assume some take- up of electric vehicles over the next 20 years in Australia, reflected by end value of WPR's portfolio. In particular, assumptions include:
- Re-leasing spreads of -5%
- Multiplying the Terminal Value by 75%, implying that 25% of VVR's sites will have limited value at the end of the leases (EV risk)
- 25bps of cap rate compression.
Our Bear Case is predicated upon an improvement in technology to the point where there is a vast take- up of electric vehicles. As such, key inputs to reflect this include:

- Multiplying Terminal Value by 60% 
- Assuming leasing spread of -25%, accounting for lower fuel profits 
- 100bps of cap rate expansion.

Equal-weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Not-Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.
